On the same token, what if a user puts in this?

/* yo */ %%cleanup /* yo */

Your code would interpret this as a single multi-line comment, which is both unexpected and incorrect.

If the mRadioState == kRadioStateRx at the time this call is made then there exists some amount of unaccounted rx time by this call.  Conceivably the radio could be in Rx for a quite some time and this discrepancy could then become a significant percentage of the total.  What if this function were written as;

return (mRadioState == kRadioStateRx) ? mRxTotal + TimerMilli::GetNow() - mLastChange : mRxTotal;

Similar logic could exist for GetRadioTxTotalTime().

This mock object is now no longer frozen when we return it. In practice, this probably doesn't matter because the only attribute we defined was `_func` and it'd be very unusual for a user of this function to change this value.

With that said, I see no reason it can't be frozen. What if we changed the definition of `__setattr__` above to something like:
```
def __setattr__(self, name, value):
    """ Set attributes on the underlying _mock if the FreezableMock is frozen.

    In cases of return_value and side_effect, these attributes are always passed
    through to the instance's _mock.

    """
    if self._frozen:
        if name in self._frozen_set:
            raise AttributeError('Cannot change frozen attribute ' + name)
        else:
            return setattr(self._mock, name, value)
   
    if name != '_frozen_set':
        self._frozen_set.add(name)

    if name in ('return_value', 'side_effect',):
        return setattr(self._mock, name, value)
    else:
        return object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
```
With this approach, the way a `FreezableMock` object works is still consistent. We do treat `return_value` and `side_effect` specially, but I personally think this is just making good use of the tools available to us to avoid reinventing the wheel than an ugly hack.

Note: With this approach, the `return_value` parameter to `__init__` would have to be modified slightly. I think this can be done by setting `self.return_value = return_value` before `self._frozen` is defined but after defining `self._mock`.

